        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>For our science case, it is vital to measure the molecular gas mass using the lowest CO(1-0) transition, which minimises the assumptions made to estimate the molecular gas mass. At a redshift z=0.013, the CO(1-0) emission line from our target will lie at 113GHz, within Band 3.

In order to achieve the best possible sensitivity, we will use the dual polarisation mode. For the spectral window tuned to the CO(1-0) emission line, we selected the Frequency Division Mode for the spectral window tracing the CO line, which will result in a spectral resolution of ~10km/s per channel. We expect the CO line from individual regions of the galaxy to have line widths on the order of a few tens of km/s, and thus to convincingly detect the line emission, we need to keep the spectral resolution at 10km/s per channel. In regions of the galaxy where the line is poorly detected, we can bin up the spectra to increase the signal-to-noise.

For the other spectral windows, we selected the Time Division Mode, since here we are interested in detecting the continuum emission and we wish to limit the data rate.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our science goal is to study the vicinity of the GRB explosion site within its host galaxy, which requires us to achieve a spatial resolution of 500pc, corresponding to 1.8" at the redshift of the host galaxy, z=0.013. At spatial scales larger than 500pc, the environmental properties measured are no longer representative of the conditions nearby to the GRB (Niino et al. 2015), and instead are indicative of the average properties of the galaxy.

We are interested in detecting emission on molecular cloud and HII region scales, which do not exceed kpc scales. We are therefore not interested in detecting emission on larger scales than a few kpc, corresponding to ~10arcsec.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Based on our MUSE data we measure a total SFR of ~0.5Msol/yr, corresponding to an expected L'co=1.3x10^8 K km/s pc^2. This corresponds to a velocity integrated flux density Ico=17.6Jy km/s, and a flux density Sco=117.6mJy if we assume a flat emission line with velocity width 150km/s, as observed in the host galaxy of GRB020819B (Hatsukade et al. 2014).

The angular extent of our target is ~70"x18". Thus, assuming a CO gas filling factor of 10%, we require a 0.6mJy RMS per 1.8arcsec^2 (corresponding to ~500pc^2) to achieve a 5sigma detection. This sensitivity is obtained with 1.6hours on-source, corresponding to a toal time of 2.5hrs (assuming a pwv of 5.186mm; 7th octile).

Within the same observing time, we will achieve a 3mm continuum RMS of 0.01mJy. Based on our broadband SED analysis, we expect the total 3mm free-free emission to be 0.4mJy. Assuming a filling factor of 10%, we should detect the continuum emission at the 5sigma level on resolution scales of ~1kpc (i.e. 4" scales).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
