        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In order to judge whether there is a deficit in H2 relative to the dust mass at the position of the GRB, we need to spatially resolve the dust emission, and this is best achieved with Band 7, which is close to the peak of the thermal dust emission (&gt;100mum), while still being fairly efficient. 

In order to achieve the best possible sensitivity, we will use the dual polarisation mode. For the spectral windows tuned to continuum emission, we selected the Time Division Mode in order to limit the data rate. 

For the spectral window tuned to the CO(3-2) emission line, we selected the Frequency Division Mode, which will result in a spectral resolution of ~850m/s. We will therefore have to bin the spectrum to obtain a significant signal.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our science goal is to study the vicinity of the GRB explosion site within its host galaxy, which requires us to achieve a spatial resolution of 500pc, corresponding to 1.8" at the redshift of the host galaxy, z=0.013. At spatial scales larger than 500pc, the environmental properties measured are no longer representative of the conditions nearby to the GRB (Niino et al. 2015), and instead are indicative of the average properties of the galaxy. 

We are interested in detecting emission on molecular cloud and HII region scales, which do not exceed kpc scales. We are therefore not interested in detecting emission on larger scales than a couple of kpc, corresponding to 7arcsec.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Based on our galaxy-whole broad band SED analysis, we estimate a flux density of 12.5mJy at 0.9mm. The angular extent of our target is ~70"x18". Thus assuming a CO gas filling factor of 30%, we require a 0.02mJy RMS per 1.8arcsec^2 (corresponding to ~500pc^2) to achieve a 5sigma detection. This sensitivity is obtained with 1.7hrs on-source, corresponding to a total time 3.4hrs (assuming a pwv of 0.913mm; 3rd octile).

Within the same observing time, we will achieve an RMS of 1.7mJy per 1.8arcsec^2 at restframe 345.796GHz, corresponding to the CO(3-2) transition line. We thus expect to detect this line at 3sigma if CO(3-2)/CO(1-0)&gt;2, as is observed in normal star-forming galaxies (Dannerbauer et al. 2009).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
