    <prp:abstract>Long-duration gamma-ray bursts (GRBs) offer a unique and detailed view of the environmental properties within star forming regions independent of galaxy luminosity or distance. Their short-lived but luminous afterglows illuminate the intervening medium, revealing an abundance of absorption features from atomic gas, metals and dust. Despite this fortuitous vantage point, there has been a striking paucity in the detection of molecular gas, both in absorption and emission. This result is truly perplexing given the indisputable link between GRBs and star formation, the abundance of neutral atomic gas, and the inexplicably small H2-to-dust mass ratio implied. We propose to combine our highly sensitive MUSE observations of the nearby and metal-rich host galaxy GRBH111005A with ALMA CO(1-0) line and 0.9mm dust emission data to study in unprecedented detail the galaxy atomic and molecular gas on ~500pc scales. Only on combining molecular gas and dust measurements with stellar and atomic gas data that are on sub-kiloparsec scales, will we be able to reliably identify the origin of the apparent H2 deficit and its implication on whether GRBs trace the cosmic star formation.</prp:abstract>
